### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

When using the new built-in control flow (`@if`/`@else`) to conditionally render a component that uses content projection (`<ng-content>`), the projected content is incorrectly rendered within the inactive branch's `<ng-content>` slot (the `@else `block), or only renders if a subsequent `<ng-content>` slot exists in the template.

In the provided example, the component acts as a wrapper that can render as either an `<a>` link or a `<button>`, using a single, non-selector `<ng-content>` for projection in both branches. When the `@if` condition is true (rendering the `<a> `tag), the content intended for the `<a>` tag's projection slot is instead rendered in the subsequent `<button>` tag's projection slot, which resides in the inactive `@else` block.

This suggests that the content projection mechanism is not properly scoped to the active `@if` block when a non-selector `<ng-content>` is present in both branches.

```
// button-wrapper.component.ts

import { Component, Input } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-button-wrapper',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    @if (asLinkTag) {
      <a [class]="buttonClass" [href]="linkHref" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        <!-- FIRST <ng-content> SLOT (Expected to render here when asLinkTag is true) -->
        <ng-content></ng-content>
      </a>
    } @else {
      <button [class]="buttonClass">
        <!-- SECOND <ng-content> SLOT (Actual location where content is rendering) -->
        <ng-content></ng-content>
      </button>
    }
  `,
})
export class ButtonWrapperComponent {
  @Input() asLinkTag = false;
  @Input() buttonClass = 'p-2 bg-blue-500 text-white rounded';
  @Input() linkHref = '#';
}
```

