### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

Yes

At least when comparing `platformBrowser().bootstrapModule()` to `bootstrapApplication()`. An Angular developer would expect to be able to use platform initializers with `bootstrapApplication` and it should not prevent them from migrating from `platformBrowser` to `bootstrapApplication`.

I see no mention of this limitation in the documentation so I assume that platform initializers are expected to work with `bootstrapApplication`.

### Description

When using `bootstrapApplication` and providing a platform initializer either via `providePlatformInitializer` or `PLATFORM_INITIALIZER`, the specified initializer function is never called.

**Example using `bootstrapApplication`**

```typescript
bootstrapApplication(AppComponent, {
  providers: [
    providePlatformInitializer(() => {
      console.log('[providePlatformInitializer] Platform initialized');
    }),
    {
      provide: PLATFORM_INITIALIZER,
      multi: true,
      useValue: () => {
        console.log('[PLATFORM_INITIALIZER] Platform initialized');
      },
    },
  ],
}).catch(error => console.log(error));
```

No output in either case. As seen in the reproduction link, I have tried performing side effects other than logging to the browser console.

In NgModule-based applications, we use `platformBrowser` or `platformBrowserDynamic` and pass an argument to its `extraProviders` parameter. Here, it works as expected.

**Example using `platformBrowser` and `PlatformRef.bootstrapModule`**

```typescript
platformBrowser([
    providePlatformInitializer(() => {
      console.log('[providePlatformInitializer] Platform initialized');
    }),
    {
      provide: PLATFORM_INITIALIZER,
      multi: true,
      useValue: () => {
        console.log('[PLATFORM_INITIALIZER] Platform initialized');
      },
    },
])
  .bootstrapModule(AppModule)
  .catch(error => console.log(error));
```

